        Flu Vaccine Options   Which flu vaccine is right for your kids? Should they get a flu shot, FluMist, or how about the new flu vaccine options, like the high-dose flu shot?   Read More   2011-2012 Flu Season    Flu Season    Flu Symptoms    Avoiding the Flu    Pediatrics Spotlight10         Vaccines in the News  
 Monday November 28, 2011   It is not unusual for vaccines to make the news, but today there was news on a lot of different vaccine topics from the American Academy of Pediatrics. 

 One study, "Immunogenicity and Safety of MMRV and PCV-7 Administered Concomitantly in Healthy Children," should reassure many parents who are worried about vaccines. The study, which will be printed in the December issue of Pediatrics, found that it was safe to give toddlers  ProQuad  (a vaccine that combines MMR and Varivax) and  Prevnar  at the same time. The researchers found this combination of shots to be well tolerated and  "highly immunogenic" as just over 1,000 children were followed for 28 days after they received the shots together or six weeks apart. 

 The AAP also released a policy statement with the latest ACIP recommendations for the use of meningococcal vaccines, including  Menactra  and Menveo. The policy statement talks about the rationale for some of latest recommendations, including the addition of a primary vaccine series for high risk infants and a booster dose for teens at age 16 years if they got their first dose when they were 11 to 12 years old. 

 Another vaccine study, this one on the varicella vaccination program, should also be reassuring to many parents. The study found that following the routine use of the chicken pox vaccine, from 1995 to 2008, chicken pox decreased almost 90% in infants, who are too young to be vaccinated. This shows a "substantial indirect benefit" to getting kids vaccinated, which is especially important since chicken pox can be a serious infection for infants, "who are at increased risk for varicella-related hospitalization and death compared with older children." 

 We will have to wait to see the effects of one last study, "Washington State Pediatricians' Attitudes Toward Alternative Childhood Immunization Schedules." The internet-based survey found that 77% of pediatricians who responded reported that their parents sometimes or frequently requested  alternative childhood immunization schedules . And 61% of the pediatricians were comfortable with following an alternative immunization schedule. Perhaps that is why Washington had the highest rate of vaccine exemptions for kids entering kindergarten during the 2009 to 2010 school year. 

 Of course it is not just vaccines that have been in the news lately. Vaccine preventable diseases have made the news a lot too, especially the  measles outbreaks  of the past year, at least a few of which were in Washington. 

