  Fruit and Vegetable Consumption Study  
 Wednesday November 23, 2011   Eating vegetables has been in the news this week, with the continuation of rules that classify pizza as a vegetable. 

 With the latest report from the 2010 National Youth Physical Activity and Nutrition Study (NYPANS) showing that few high school students eat their recommended number of fruits and vegetables each day, maybe we need to reclassify other foods as vegetables too. If hamburgers and hotdogs were vegetables, more high school students would do better on the survey. 

 Of course, moving foods into new  foods groups  won't do anything to improve these kids' nutrition. You can call a can of soda a glass of milk, but the child who drinks it still won't get any calcium, vitamin D, or protein like he would if he drank a real glass of milk. 


 Nutrition Study 


 In this latest nutrition study, high school students were asked "how many times during the previous 7 days they had consumed the following: fruit, 100% fruit juice, green salad, potatoes (not including French fries, fried potatoes, or potato chips), carrots, and other vegetables." 

 The results, reported by the CDC today, showed that "the median number of times per day that U.S. high school students consumed fruits and vegetables was only 1.2 times for both fruits and vegetables." The results also indicate that it is "likely that the majority of students are not meeting the daily fruit and vegetable recommendations for adolescents." 

 How do we get kids to eat more fruits and vegetables? 

 The CDC report suggests that we "include school salad bars, gardens, farm-to-school programs, the U.S. Department of Agriculture's Fresh Fruit and Vegetable Program, and increasing the amount and variety of fruits and vegetables offered during school meals." It doesn't say anything about making pizza a vegetable because it has a little tomato paste though. 

 What can you do? In addition to making  fruits  and  vegetables  more available at home, how about offering more fruits and vegetables as a part of your  Thanksgiving dinner , especially some that you haven't tried before. 

